## Documentation Sync Checklist

Code and docs drift silently — the only reliable defence is to treat
docs as part of the definition of "done".  When you change something,
update its documentation in the SAME commit, not a follow-up.  The
mapping below is concrete; audit every applicable row before you run
`git commit`.

<!-- PROJECT: This is the heart of the matrix-honesty discipline.
Each row maps "kind of change" → "doc that must be updated in the
same commit".  Start with the rows below; add your own as failure
modes surface (a stale docstring that misled a contributor → new row
about that docstring class). -->

| If you change / add … | Then touch … |
|---|---|
| A new interactive HTML element (button, input, link, row, `<select>`, `<option>`) | `<your project's testid reference doc>` — document the new `data-testid` in the appropriate page section.  *(Only applies if your project has a UI tested with stable selectors.)* |
| A new `<COMPONENT>` under `<core/>` | The top-level `README.md` (if it lists components) and `ARCHITECTURE.md` (if a new pattern). |
| A new public function or endpoint | Its docstring (Google-style sections for Args / Returns / Raises) — and the module docstring if it enumerates contents. |
| A function gains a new parameter or changes return shape | Its docstring.  Stale `Args:` lists are a top-three source of contributor confusion. |
| A pipeline-stage signature (frozen for API stability) | **DON'T.**  Add a NEW function instead; the module docstring tracks which are frozen.  *(Only applies if you have frozen public-surface contracts.)* |
| A new pytest marker in `pyproject.toml` or a fixture that meaningfully changes how a whole test tier runs | `tests/README.md` — markers without doc entries are invisible to contributors running `pytest -m <name>`. |
| A new hard rule / cross-cutting invariant surfaced by a bug | This file — add to the "Hard Rules (Never Break)" section with a one-line rationale pointing at the failure mode. |
| A capability / feature declaration changes (a `<COMPONENT>` flips between supported / lossy / unsupported) | Matching test or expectation file under `<your project's expectation directory>`.  *(Only applies if your project has explicit capability declarations.)* |
| A file-tree listing or "contents map" in any doc | Either update the listing in the same commit as the new file, OR convert the listing to a pointer ("see `<directory>/` for the current set").  Exhaustive inventories that enumerate every file become a maintenance tax — prefer one-line pointers unless the enumeration carries load-bearing explanation. |
| `<CORE_ABSTRACTION>` gains a new field | The walkthrough doc for "adding a field to `<CORE_ABSTRACTION>`" — the worked example must stay accurate.  *(Only applies if your project has a single central data model.)* |
| A new `<EXTERNAL_INTEGRATION>` (vendor, plugin, backend) | The README's integration list and the worked example doc for "adding a `<EXTERNAL_INTEGRATION>`". |
| The Nth commit (3-5+) of a thematic series shipping pieces of the same conceptual subsystem | `ARCHITECTURE.md` — at the Nth commit, ask: "does the architecture doc have a section describing this concept, or only the piecemeal mechanics?"  If the concept is absent, add a short section in that same commit. |

Rule of thumb: if a future contributor could plausibly search for the
thing you just added and not find its rationale, there's a doc gap to
close.

