## Hard Rules (Never Break)

These are invariants surfaced by real bugs.  Each rule has a one-line
rationale because abstract guidance gets ignored.  When a new bug
surfaces a new invariant, add it here in the same commit that fixes
the bug.

<!-- PROJECT: The list below is GENERIC scaffolding — every project
benefits from these.  Add your project-specific rules in the
PROJECT-SPECIFIC RULES section below as failure modes surface. -->

### Generic rules (apply to most projects)

- **Never** commit real credentials, secrets, API keys, or production
  identifiers (IPs, hostnames, real customer names) — even in test
  fixtures.  Synthetic test data should LOOK realistic but be
  obviously fake (e.g. `192.0.2.x` from RFC 5737, `device-1`,
  `$5$REDACTED$REDACTED01`).
- **Never** skip pre-commit hooks (`--no-verify`) or bypass signing
  unless the user has explicitly asked for it.  If a hook fails,
  investigate and fix the underlying issue — the hook is doing what
  it's there for.
- **Never** patch external SDK clients (e.g. SSH library, HTTP
  client, third-party API wrapper) directly in tests.  Patch the
  project's single factory / dependency-injection point instead.
  Multiple patch sites drift apart and create flaky tests that pass
  individually but fail in the suite.
  <!-- PROJECT: Replace with your project's actual factory point.
  In Netcanon this is `netcanon.api.routes.backups.get_collector`. -->
- **Never** land a code change without updating the docs it renders
  stale.  The Documentation Sync Checklist above is concrete — if a
  row applies to your change, touch the listed doc in the same
  commit.  Stale docs are a bug; they just don't crash loud enough
  to be caught by CI, which is why the discipline has to live in the
  workflow.
- **Never** hard-code a count, LOC figure, test tally, or other
  number-that-changes in prose documentation unless the same commit
  adds a CI / test guard that keeps the number honest.  Use
  qualitative phrasing ("the largest module in the app", "dozens of
  fixtures across N integrations") or link to the authoritative
  source (`pytest --collect-only`, the file itself, the live
  results doc).  Numbers in *test assertions* fail loudly and are
  fine; numbers in *prose* rot silently.
- **Never** make active lies in operator-facing messages, docstrings,
  or capability declarations.  If a feature is half-shipped, declare
  the half that doesn't work as `unsupported` (or whatever your
  project's "we don't do this" tier is called).  Silently dropping
  data the user supplied is a worse outcome than a banner saying
  "this section was not translated."
- **Never** change the signatures of frozen public-surface functions.
  External callers and tests depend on the exact shape.  Later phases
  add NEW public functions; existing surfaces stay frozen.
  <!-- PROJECT: Identify your frozen surfaces explicitly.  In
  Netcanon the migration_pipeline.py public functions are frozen. -->
- **Never** assert on a request's *initial* response body for final
  job state on async / background-task endpoints — the initial
  response always serialises before the task runs.  Always poll /
  re-fetch by ID to read the completed state.
  <!-- PROJECT: Drop this rule if your project doesn't have async
  job endpoints. -->

