## Operator-trust language

When writing operator-facing copy (error messages, banners, validation
output, docstrings consumed via help text), apply the matrix-honesty
discipline to the *language*:

* **Don't claim what you can't deliver.** "Migration successful" when
  half the source was silently dropped is a lie that erodes trust at
  exactly the moment the operator can't catch it.
* **Don't over-warn until operators tune you out.** A warning on every
  page becomes invisible.  Warn on real problems; trust the operator
  to read the explicit "this is what we don't do" page.
* **Name the boundary.**  When you decline to do something, say *why*
  in operator-relevant terms (not implementation terms).  "This tool
  doesn't auto-translate firewall rules because cross-vendor semantics
  don't translate cleanly — see CAPABILITIES.md" is a useful
  declination; "Tier 3 unsupported" alone is a non-answer.

